		<b>Comment By Tom Chambers, 8-09-05</b>
		<p>Read your article with interest. We have a prairie dog town that has been doubling in size every 18 months. It now consumes about 60 acres. The grass in that part of our pasture is 0-1/4" long. Normally it is 12-24" long. Experts at the Dept. of Agriculture recommend immediate control. I certainly feel as connected to the land and its animals as anyone and am seeking alternatives to poison or explosives. Hopefully you can help. Please don't refer me to more articles and studies as I've read dozens. Do you know of a relocation solution or an experimental method? Perhaps you can forward this to contacts used in your research. We are located between Big Timber and Harlowtown in MT. <br />
<br />
Thank you in advance.<br />
Tom Chambers</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Jenny Shank, 8-10-05</b>
		<p>Unfortunately, I'm not an expert in prairie dog control, but I bet that if you contacted the people at City of Boulder who are in charge of praire dog control, they could give you some advice, because they have a lot of experience with landowners who have a similar problem, and have used relocation extensively.  The contact info is at this page:<br />
<a href="http://www.newwest.net/?URL=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.ci.boulder.co.us%2Fplanning%2FPrairieDogs%2Fcontact_info.htm">http://www.ci.boulder.co.us/planning/PrairieDogs/contact_info.htm</a><br />
<br />
Most of the other organizations that I looked into for this article seem to either be on the side of shooting or poisoning prairie dogs or not allowing them to be harmed under any circumstances, but Boulder city government has had to balance the two factions.<br />
<br />
Good luck!  I hope they don't eat you out of house & home.</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Tom Chambers, 8-12-05</b>
		<p>Thanks for your advice. I talked with Bev at City of Boulder. She said re-location has worked but is very expensive and itâ€™s extremely difficult to find areas that will accept prairie dogs. Also itâ€™s usually done only on small acreages. <br />
<br />
According to Bev there have been experiments with plastic weed barriers like those found along highway construction areas, but results proved unsuccessful. Various types of fencing have been tried, also proving ineffective. They are playing around with a mesh material, which is laid over the ground to prevent further dog holes from popping up.  <br />
<br />
Bev referred me to Wild Places, a non-profit specializing in prairie dogs. Iâ€™ve left 2 messages without response. <br />
<br />
Bev also recommended Roe Ecological services, a for profit contractor. Kelly was very helpful and accommodating. She gave me a rough estimate of $600/ acre (about $36,000 in our case) to live trap 90-95% of our prairie dogs. They would then be euthanised and used as captive raptor food. Or the dogs could be relocated at an additional cost, if a site could be found. <br />
<br />
Kelly also mentioned Dog-Gone, the guys with the giant vacuum that sucks prairie dogs from their holes. She estimated their price to do our 60 acres at $250,000! <br />
<br />
Both these options are way beyond our budget. We are looking for organizations that may cost share or subsidize a relocation project. I have left messages with The Nature Conservancy and the Ferret Program. <br />
<br />
Apparently they sell for $300 in Japan as pets. Iâ€™ll give them free to any willing entrepreneur. At 10 dogs/acre x 60 acresâ€¦.thatâ€™s $180,000! Where else can you get a return like that?<br />
<br />
Let me know if you or your readers have any other thoughts on how to control these pesky persistent little buggers without killinâ€™ â€˜em or going broke. <br />
<br />
Thanks,<br />
Tom Chambers<br />
AKA: Bill Murray</p>
		
